<h1 class="rm-manual">Flash is being removed from Windows soon - but there's a catch</h1>
<p class="rm-manual"> By <span><a href="https://www.techradar.com/uk/author/mike-moore" rel="author"><span>Mike Moore</span></a></span> 07 September 2020 </p>
<p>Flash may see its days as numbered, but Microsoft isn't pulling the plug just yet</p>
<figcaption> <span>(Image credit: Pixabay)</span> </figcaption><p>Microsoft has announced it will be ending support for <a href="https://www.techradar.com/uk/news/internet/the-long-and-painful-death-of-flash-1324425">Adobe Flash Player</a> soon.</p>
<p>The much-maligned Flash will no longer be supported on Microsoft's 
web browsers after December 31 2020 as the technology firm looks to 
ensure customers are secured online.</p>
<p>Flash will be removed from Microsoft's browsers with the upcoming launch of <a href="https://www.techradar.com/uk/news/flash-is-being-phased-out-of-microsoft-edge">Edge</a> v88 in January 2021, with Internet Explorer 11 also waving goodbye alongside Microsoft Edge Legacy.</p>
